executor_description: This endpoint runs evaluation by a selected credit policy (present in the route) on a selected monitoring list (that is sent in the request's body).
You can create a new enterprise credit policy with a POST request to /account/enterprise_credit_policies/create. The POST request must contain all of the following keys:

If you are trying to enable (deploy) an enterprise credit policy, a validation process is run on it to check whether the policy is in a correct format. This endpoint makes it possible to run the same validation process without trying to enable a policy which can be useful if you do not wish deploy your policy but you want to know if it is built without errors.

To update an enterprise credit policy, send a POST request to this endpoint with the ID of the policy in the route. The body of the request is in the same format as what is used by the Create endpoint - the only difference is that you are not required to send every property (besides country), so you can just send the ones you would like to update, eg. {"country": "DK", "name": "Updated test policy"}

executor_description: This end-point is used to verify if you have already subscribed to a company. Example of use is to change the subscribe button on the Risika Dashboard, if you already subscribed to the company.
This end-point is meant to show a brief overview of the 3 most important changes in a monitoring list. This is the end-point used in "Most relevant changes" on the Risika Dashboard.

Use this end-point to get a complete list of the IDs and names of your monitoring lists as well as the owners and users that were granted with access to the lists - for public lists, the owner and the list_user properties are null. Some lists may be omitted, if you haven't been granted visibility rights Monitoring Visibility. The endpoint also gives a brief overview of the risk distribution for each list. The risk can be used to sort or prioritize the lists.

You can add companies to your monitoring lists by sending a POST request with the Company IDs you want to subscribe to /monitor/add. It will not raise an error, if you're already subscribed to the company. If you add an invalid Company ID, it will return the ID in the response under rejected.

This end-point will remove a monitoring list and all companies subscribed to it. It is not possible to recover a list, when it has been removed. Public lists can be removed by any user, but private lists can be only removed by their owner.

To remove companies from the monitoring list, call this end-point with a list of Company IDs to remove. Unlike Add Monitoring, this end-point will return an error, if you try to remove a company you haven't subscribed to.

You always have one monitoring list with ID 0, which cannot be removed. If you need more lists, you can always create more with this end-point. When you first create a list, you can choose a name for it and you will get a unique ID of that list back. If you want to change the name after creation, see Rename Monitoring List It is optional to send the key private in the payload, where if it's true, the list will be only visible for the creator, and if it's false, the list will be public inside the company. If you do not send this key, the list will be created as private by default.

Get a complete list of the companies you monitor together with the most recent changes. Monitoring supports having multiple lists, which can be managed with a list_id. The list_id (integer) is set in the URI (see request example).

asset_turnover.explanation: The asset turnover shows the relationship between the firm’s revenue and its total assets. Thereby, the asset turnover expresses the firm’s ability to generate revenue in direct proportion to its total assets.

basic_earning_power.explanation: The Basic Earning Power ratio shows the relationship between the firm’s earnings before deduction of interest and tax (EBIT) and its total assets. The ratio is a measurement for the firm’s earning power before the effect of taxes and financial leverage. The ratio belongs to the ratios known as profitability ratios. The company has a very weak Basic Earning Power ratio (BEP), because it is within the 20% lowest rated companies in the same industry.

capacity_ratio.explanation: The capacity ratio shows the relationship between the firm’s gross result and its gross result with EBIT subtracted. The capacity ratio expresses in what magnitude the fixed costs have affected the firm’s gross result. By that means, a high capacity ratio is indicating that the fixed costs have had a minor influence on the earnings from the basic operations and vice versa. The capacity ratio belongs to the ratios known as profitability ratios. The company has a very weak Capacity ratio, because it is within the 20% lowest rated companies in the same industry.

cash_conversion_rate.explanation: The cash conversion ratio shows the relationship the firm’s cash flow and its profit. Therefore, the cash conversion ratio can be interpreted as the firm’s ability to convert profits into accessible cash. The cash conversion ratio belongs to the ratios known as liquidity ratios. The company has a average Cash conversion ratio (CCR), compared to other companies in the same industry.

cash_ratio.explanation: The cash ratio shows the relationship between the firm’s cash and its short-term debt. The cash ratio is a measurement of the firm’s liquidity and belongs to the ratios known as liquidity ratios. More specifically, it expresses the firm’s ability to repay its short-term debt solely with cash. The cash ratio is useful to creditors when determining how much to issue in terms of loans. The company has a very strong Cash ratio, because it is within the 20% highest rated companies in the same industry.

current_assets_to_equity.explanation: The current assets to equity ratio shows the relationship between the firm’s current assets and its equity. The ratio is an indicator of the firm’s horizontal balance structure and provides insight in both the firm’s short-term and long-term financing activities. The ratio belongs to the ratios known as liquidity ratios. In terms of interpretation of the level of the ratio, it is highly industry dependent. The company has a strong Current assets to equity ratio, because it is within the 30% highest rated companies in the same industry.

current_ratio.explanation: The current ratio shows the relationship between the company’s current assets and its short-term debt. The current ratio indicates the company’s ability to settle its short-term debt solely by applying its current assets. In a credit rating perspective, a satisfying current ratio is around 150%. The company has a strong liquidity ratio, because it is within the 30% highest rated companies in the same industry.

debt_ratio.explanation: The debt ratio shows the relationship between the firm’s debt in total and its balance sheet total. The debt ratio expresses the proportion of the total assets financed by debt. By that means, a high debt ratio denotes that the firm’s assets are financed primarily by debt. Inversely, a lower debt ratio denotes that the firm’s assets are financed primarily by equity. The debt ratio belongs to the ratios known as debt ratios. The company has a average Debt ratio, compared to other companies in the same industry.

debt_to_equity_ratio.explanation: The debt-to-equity ratio shows the relationship between the company’s debt and equity and indicates the company’s leverage. A higher level of the debt-to-equity ratio indicates a higher reliance on debt-financing.  The company has a average gearing, compared to other companies in the same industry.

ebitda_to_debt_ratio.explanation: The EBITDA to debt ratio shows the relationship between the firm’s earnings before interest, taxes depreciation and amortization (EBITDA) and its debt. The EBITDA to debt ratio is a measurement of the earnings (EBITDA) availability to fulfill debt payments before covering interest, taxes depreciation and amortization expenses. The EBITDA to debt ratio belongs to the ratios known as debt ratios. The company has a very weak EBITDA to debt ratio, because it is within the 20% lowest rated companies in the same industry.

equity_to_contributed_capital_ratio.explanation: The equity to contributed capital ratio shows the relationship between the firm’s total equity and its contributed capital. By that means, the ratio is an indicator of the magnitude of the equity in proportion to the contributed capital. Moreover, the ratio indicates the development of the equity with the contributed capital being the starting point. The company has a strong Equity to contributed capital ratio, because it is within the 30% highest rated companies in the same industry.

fixed_assets_to_long_term_liabilities_ra.explanation: The fixed assets to long term liabilities ratio shows the relationship between the firm’s fixed assets and its long-term capital (equity and long-term liabilities). With regards to the firm’s liquidity position, the ratio should be below 100%. Thereby, the firm has more long-term capital than fixed assets indicating that the long-term capital is financing considerably more than merely fixed assets. The ratio belongs to the ratios known as liquidity ratios. The company has a weak Fixed assets to long term capital ratio, because it is within the 40% lowest rated companies in the same industry.

gross_margin.explanation: The gross margin shows the relationship between the firm’s gross result and its revenue. The gross margin expresses the proportion of the revenue solely used for covering the firm’s fixed costs. Moreover, the gross margin gives an indication of the magnitude of the variable costs. For instance, a low gross margin indicates that the firm’s variable costs have significant impact on the gross result.

income_to_debt_ratio.explanation: The income-to-debt ratio shows the relationship between the firm’s profit and debt. The income-to-debt ratio is an expression of the firm’s ability to create earnings by operating with debt. The ratio belongs to the ratios known as leveraging ratios. The company has a very weak Income-to-debt ratio, because it is within the 20% lowest rated companies in the same industry.

interest_coverage.explanation: Interest coverage is the ability to repay interest on debt. The company has a very weak interest coverage, because it is within the 20% lowest rated companies in the same industry.

interest_margin.explanation: The interest margin shows the relationship between the firm’s return on assets (ROA) and its interest rate on debt. The interest margin is calculated as the return on assets minus the interest rate on debt. A positive interest margin, where return on assets is greater than the interest rate on debt, indicates that the firm benefits from operating with debt. Inversely, a negative interest margin indicates that the firm is worse off operating with debt. The company has a very weak Interest margin / Interest differential, because it is within the 20% lowest rated companies in the same industry.

interest_rate_on_debt_with_average.explanation: The interest rate on debt shows the relationship between the firm’s financial expenses and its total liabilities. By that means, the interest rate on debt expresses that particular interest rate the firm pays for its liabilities. The interest rate on debt belongs to the ratios known as debt ratios. The company has a weak Interest rate on debt, because it is within the 30% lowest rated companies in the same industry.

inventory_conversion_ratio.explanation: The inventory conversion ratio shows the relationship between the firm’s revenue and its inventories. The ratio expresses the amount of times the firm has sold and replaced its inventory annually. A low inventory conversion ratio may indicate weakened sales or perhaps excess inventory.

liabilities_to_equity_ratio.explanation: Liabilities to equity ratio shows the relationship between the firm’s liabilities and its equity. The liabilities to equity ratio is indicating whether the firm operates primarily through liabilities or equity. The liabilities to equity ratio belongs to the ratios known as debt ratios. The company has a average Liabilities to equity ratio, compared to other companies in the same industry.

one_year_change_in_debt.explanation: One year change in debt is calculated as current year’s debt divided by last year’s debt. With that, one year change in debt is indicating the level of either an increase or a decrease in the firm’s debt. The company has a very weak One year change in debt, because it is within the 10% lowest rated companies in the same industry.

one_year_change_in_equity.explanation: One year change in equity is calculated as equity divided by equity minus profit for the year. One year change in equity is indicating the level of either an increase or a decrease in the firm’s equity in the current year. The company has a strong One year change in equity, because it is within the 40% highest rated companies in the same industry.

operating_margin.explanation: The operating margin shows the relationship between the firm’s EBIT and its revenue. By that means, the operating margin shows the proportion of the revenue that remains as earnings after covering of all operating costs. Therefore, the operating margin becomes a significant key figure for assessment of a firm’s earning power.

profit_margin.explanation: The net profit margin shows the relationship between the firm’s profit for the year and its revenue. The net profit margin expresses the firm’s ability to create profit in direct proportion to its revenue. Therefore, the net profit margin is key figure expressing the firm’s profitability.

quick_ratio.explanation: The quick ratio shows the relationship between the firm’s short-term debt and its current assets deducted inventory. By that means, the ratio is an indicator of the firm’s ability to pay its short-term debt obligations merely with its most liquid assets. A quick ratio of 1 or above implies a healthy liquidity position because all short-term debt obligations can be paid off with only those current assets that can be instantly liquidated. The company has a strong Quick ratio, because it is within the 30% highest rated companies in the same industry.

return_on_assets.explanation: The return on assets (ROA) shows the company’s net profit/loss as a percentage of the assets of the company. The return on assets indicates the rate of return on the capital employed. The company has a very weak return on assets, because it is within the 20% lowest rated companies in the same industry.

return_on_equity.explanation: The return on equity (ROE) shows the company’s net profit/loss as a percentage of the equity. The return on equity indicates the rate of return the equity investors have earned on their investment the current year. Thus, return on equity is a measure of the profitability. The company has a very weak return on equity, because it is within the 10% lowest rated companies in the same industry.

return_on_net_assets.explanation: The return on net assets ratio (RONA) shows the relationship between the firm’s income and its net-assets. The ratio belongs to the ratios known profitability ratios and expresses the firm’s ability to generate profits solely from its net-assets. Net-assets is defined as total assets with a subtraction of total debt. The company has a very weak Return on net assets (RONA), because it is within the 10% lowest rated companies in the same industry.

solidity_ratio.explanation: The solidity ratio shows the proportion of the company’s assets that have been financed by equity. The solidity ratio indicates the company’s ability to survive potential losses. In a credit rating perspective, a satisfying solidity ratio is around 40%. The company has a average solidity, compared to other companies in the same industry.
